# Lead UX Designer — When to Invoke

For **UX-related** work, invoke the **lead-ux-designer** subagent (via the **Task** tool, `subagent_type: lead-ux-designer`) when **there is no clearly defined method** already in place—e.g. no matching pattern in the app, no ticket/design spec, or you are inventing new copy, states, or flows.

## Invoke (proactively)

- **New or changed user-facing flows** (steps, empty/loading/error states, modals, wizards).
- **Substantial copy** (empty states, tooltips, confirmations, admin labels) where tone, clarity, or consistency with the rest of the product matters.
- **New UI patterns** or deviations from how similar surfaces behave elsewhere.
- **Accessibility or layout** choices that affect how users perceive or complete a task (not just a one-line class tweak).

**Prompt should include:** route(s) or feature name, current copy or structure, constraints (e.g. dark admin theme, character limits), and what decision you need (e.g. “review empty states + tab labels”).

## Skip (main agent only)

- **Mechanical** application of an **existing** documented or in-code pattern (same component, same copy formula as sibling pages).
- **Purely technical** changes with **no** user-visible behavior or copy (types, API, refactors).
- **User supplied exact** copy or a **linked spec** that already defines behavior; only invoke if you still need a consistency or a11y pass.
- **Trivial** fixes (typos, obvious bug copy like a missing period) unless they sit in a sensitive flow (auth, payment, legal).

## After the subagent returns

Integrate feedback into the implementation (or explain why not). Do not treat the subagent as optional decoration when the change matched **Invoke** above—the goal is **consistent** use of UX review when the method is not already defined.

